markw wrote:

&gt; A couple of very mundane points:
&gt;
&gt; Go for RMI over IIOP from the start - its easy using the POA in 
&gt; recent CORBA. My experience of RMI under load is that it&#39;s a bit 
&gt; flaky and what&#39;s worse is that its &#39;flaky&#39; as opposed to right out 
&gt; breaking so you find the odd call not happening properly. I did a 
&gt; fair amount of load testing on it and decided that it was 
&gt; rubbish :-). I also load tested RMI over IIOP and couldn&#39;t manage to 
&gt; load it enough to break it at all.
&gt;
Ok.  Thanks.  I&#39;ve heard this from others also.

&gt; I&#39;ve used JMS in JBoss quite a lot too and you might find that it 
&gt; provides a good way of providing resilience as machines come and go. 
&gt; I can&#39;t remember the ins and outs but from what I remember one of the 
&gt; configurations don&#39;t cope well with lots of small messages though.
&gt;
Ok. Its something to look at for sure.  As long as we implement against 
JMS interfaces, we can also try other providers (I&#39;ve worked with Spread 
in the past).

&gt; For dynamic configuration of the server farm have you considered 
&gt; JINI. 

Not seriously.  I&#39;ve followed it over time.  I have a bias that jini 
still needs work and would be more apt if we were coordinating 100s of 
crawlers rather the 3-10 we&#39;re currently trying to get going (3-10 will 
be more than a handful).  But I&#39;ll go look again.  Thanks for the reminder.

(Regards dynamic configuration, we&#39;re hoping that more work in JMX will 
get us this. TBD.)

&gt; Its a really nice technology for this kind of thing - you can 
&gt; add and remove components from a large system in a true &#39;plug and 
&gt; play&#39; fashion. Its a little bit fiddley to get working with &#39;pure&#39; 
&gt; J2EE but you can make it work in JBoss.


Thanks alot for the feedback Mark.
St.Ack

